<p><b><i><span style='font-size:13.5pt;color:#3333FF'>3. Architectural Support
for Robust Software Execution</span></i></b> </p>

<p>Computer program faults cause billions dollars of losses each year. Very
often, these faults are due to the bugs in the programs. For example, illegal
memory accesses may cause the whole program to fail and terminate unexpectedly,
thus causing the user to lose valuable data. While monitoring tools for
enhancing memory access integrity exist (e.g., Purify, Numega), they usually
dramatically degrade the system performance. With the advances in semiconductor
technology, there is available processing power in today's architectures that
are not fully utilized by application programs. We intend to use the available
computing power of these architectures to execute the detection routines to
enhance the crash-proofness of commodity programs. </p>

<p><b>Collaborators</b>: <br>
T. N. Vijaykumar (ECE, Purdue), Tony Hosking (CS, Purdue). </p>

<p><b>Background reading</b>: <br>
1. R. Hastings and B. Joyce: &quot;Purify: Fast detection of memory leaks and
access errors&quot;. In Proceedings of the Winter USENIX Conference, December
